The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sports

 Chennai: India?s junior men?s volleyball team retained the title, beating Hungary in the final of the 24th Memorial Ferruccio Cornacchia volleyball championship at San Giorgio de Porcia. The Indian spikers prevailed 26-24, 25-18, 28-26 in the final on Monday.

 The victory is commendable as the Indians staved off strong challenges from teams like Germany, Bulgaria and Italy en route to the summit clash. India had defeated Hungary 25-20, 25-22, 18-25, 25-21 in the final last year too. 

 Chikmagalur: India?s Prakash Amritraj advanced to the second round of the $ 25,000 Coffee Cup ATP Challenger on a day when compatriots Kiran Nandakumar and Navdeep Singh were eliminated.

 Amritraj dominated the match from the start as he registered a 6-3, 6-2 win over Henry Adjei Darko of Ghana on Tuesday.

 Nandakumar lost to Karan Rastogi 3-6, 2-6. Singh lost to Aleksandar Vlaski of Serbia Montenegro 7-6 (7-3), 6-3. 

 Sydney: New Zealand winger Jonah Lomu suffered another setback to his hopes of representing the All Blacks again when he damaged ankle ligaments playing for the Cardiff Blues on Saturday.

 The 31-year-old Lomu, who is seeking to resume his international career in time to play in the 2007 World Cup, joined the Welsh club on a short-term contract in December after two years out of action following a kidney transplant.

 Lomu became the youngest player to represent the All Blacks in 1994 and rose to prominence at the 1995 World Cup in South Africa when he almost single-handedly destroyed England in the semi-finals.

 Singapore: Golfs European Tour has stumped up $100,000 to boost the prize pot for next month?s inaugural Amby Valley Masters in India.

 The cash for the Mumbai event, the 13th leg of the Asian Tour, is being handed over as a thank you to organisers for switching dates to accommodate the co-sanctioned Indonesia Open.

 The tournament, to be played at Amby Valley Sahara Lake City from May 11-14, now boasts a purse of $400,000.

 It had originally been scheduled for February but was moved to allow the Indonesia Open to be played. 

 London: Everton midfielder Lee Carsley has appealed against his sending off against Chelsea, the FA said on Tuesday.

 Carsley was shown a straight red card two minutes after the re-start for a foul on Ivory Coast striker Didier Drogba in Monday?s Premier League game. His case will be considered by the FA?s disciplinary commission on Thursday. 

 Asuncion: Palmeiras and Cerro Porteno could face disciplinary action after their players were involved in a brawl during a Libertadores Cup tie last week, the South American confederation (CSF) said on Monday.

 The fight delayed the start of the second half 

 of the tie in Sao Paulo for nearly 10 minutes.

